Let $x = \sqrt[4]{5^4+1}$ and $y = \sqrt[4]{5^4-1}$.
Then we have $\frac{1}{\sqrt[4]{5^4+1}-\sqrt[4]{5^4-1}} = \frac{1}{x-y}$.
We have
\begin{align*} x^4 &= 5^4+1 \\ y^4 &= 5^4-1 \end{align*}
We want to rationalize the denominator.
\begin{align*} \frac{1}{x-y} &= \frac{1}{x-y} \cdot \frac{x^2+xy+y^2}{x^2+xy+y^2} \\ &= \frac{x^2+xy+y^2}{x^3-y^3} \\ &= \frac{(x^2+xy+y^2)}{(x-y)(x^2+xy+y^2)} \\ &= \frac{x^2+xy+y^2}{x^4-y^4} \\ &= \frac{x^2+xy+y^2}{(5^4+1)-(5^4-1)} \\ &= \frac{x^2+xy+y^2}{2} \\ &= \frac{(\sqrt[4]{5^4+1})^2 + \sqrt[4]{5^4+1}\sqrt[4]{5^4-1} + (\sqrt[4]{5^4-1})^2}{2} \end{align*}
We have
\begin{align*} x^4-y^4 &= (x^2+y^2)(x^2-y^2) \\ x^2+y^2 &= (\sqrt[4]{5^4+1})^2+(\sqrt[4]{5^4-1})^2 \\ &= \sqrt[4]{5^8+2\cdot 5^4+1} + \sqrt[4]{5^8-2\cdot 5^4+1} \\ x^2-y^2 &= (\sqrt[4]{5^4+1})^2-(\sqrt[4]{5^4-1})^2 \\ x^2+xy+y^2 &= \sqrt[4]{5^8+2\cdot 5^4+1} + \sqrt[4]{5^8-2\cdot 5^4+1} + \sqrt[4]{(5^4+1)(5^4-1)} \\ &= 25^2+1 \sqrt{25^4+1} \\ &\approx 625+1 \approx 626 \end{align*}
\begin{align*} \frac{1}{x-y} &\approx \frac{5^2+\sqrt{5^4^2-1^2} +5^2}{2} \\ &= \frac{5^2+\sqrt{5^8-1}+5^2}{2} \\ &= \frac{25^2+1}{2} = \frac{626}{2} = 313 \end{align*}
\begin{align*} \frac{1}{x-y} &\approx \frac{x^2+xy+y^2}{2} \\ &\approx \frac{(\sqrt[4]{626})^2+\sqrt[4]{(5^4+1)(5^4-1)}+\sqrt[4]{624}}{2} \\ &\approx \frac{(5^2)^2 + (5^2)^2}{2} = \frac{2(25^2)}{2} = 625 \end{align*}
Final Answer: $\boxed{313}$
